ğŸ“– The Story of Merge Sort

Goal:
Sort an array in ascending order.
Merge sort follows the Divide and Conquer idea:
Divide: Split the array into two halves.
Conquer: Recursively sort both halves.
Combine: Merge the two sorted halves into one sorted array.

ğŸ§© The Three Parts of the Recursion Story

1ï¸âƒ£ Base Case (The Ending)
When l >= r, it means the array has one or zero elements â€” itâ€™s already sorted.
So, we stop.

2ï¸âƒ£ Recursive Step (The Chapter Progression)
For any subarray with more than one element:
Find the middle index.
Recursively sort the left half.
Recursively sort the right half.
Then merge both halves.

3ï¸âƒ£ Leap of Faith (The Trust)
We trust recursion to correctly sort both halves â€”
our job is only to merge those sorted halves properly.

ğŸ•’ Time Complexity: O(n log n)
ğŸ’¾ Space Complexity: O(n)

class Solution { 
public: 
    void merge(vector<int>& arr, int l, int mid, int r) { 
        int n1 = mid - l + 1; 
        int n2 = r - mid; 
        vector<int> left(n1), right(n2);

        for (int k = 0; k < n1; k++) 
            left[k] = arr[l + k]; 
        for (int k = 0; k < n2; k++) 
            right[k] = arr[mid + 1 + k]; 

        int i = l, k = 0, m = 0; 

        while (k < n1 && m < n2) { 
            if (left[k] <= right[m]) 
                arr[i++] = left[k++]; 
            else 
                arr[i++] = right[m++]; 
        } 

        while (k < n1) arr[i++] = left[k++]; 
        while (m < n2) arr[i++] = right[m++]; 
    } 

    void mergeSort(vector<int>& arr, int l, int r) { 
        if (l >= r) return;  // Base case
        int mid = l + ((r - l) >> 1); 
        mergeSort(arr, l, mid);      // Sort left half
        mergeSort(arr, mid + 1, r);  // Sort right half
        merge(arr, l, mid, r);       // Merge both halves
    } 
};
